            <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center mb-2 text-indigo-600">The Impact of Neural Oscillations on Short-Term Memory</h2>
            <p class="text-center text-gray-500">Published: May 2024</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Abstract -->
        <section class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg mb-12">
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Abstract</h3>
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
                This research investigates the critical role of neural oscillations, specifically in the theta and gamma bands, in the encoding and retrieval of information in short-term memory. By analyzing EEG data from subjects performing memory-based tasks, we found a significant correlation between the power of gamma oscillations during encoding and subsequent memory recall performance. Our findings suggest a mechanistic model where theta-gamma coupling serves as a key coordinator for neural assemblies involved in memory formation.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Key Sections -->
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <!-- Methodology -->
            <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Methodology</h3>
                <p class="mb-4">
                    We employed a mixed-methods approach, combining quantitative EEG analysis with qualitative participant feedback. Participants were tasked with a series of digital memory games while their neural activity was recorded...
                </p>
                <a href="methodology.html" class="inline-block bg-indigo-600 text-white font-bold py-2 px-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-700 transition duration-300">Read More &rarr;</a>
            </div>

            <!-- Results -->
            <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Results</h3>
                <p class="mb-4">
                    The primary finding was a strong positive correlation (r=0.78, p < 0.01) between gamma-band power during the encoding phase and the accuracy of memory recall. Participants with stronger theta-gamma phase coupling also demonstrated faster reaction times.
                </p>
